This really didn't look right to me, based on my reading of Pattern (the "Backslashes, escapes, and quoting" section, in particular). However, I was wrong!
Based on some local testing, both of these code samples work (i.e. print out "fixed"):
This:
public static void main(String[] args) {
  String valueToFix = "Howdy!\u0000";
  String valueFixed = valueToFix.replaceAll("\u0000", "");
  if (valueToFix.contentEquals(valueFixed))
    System.out.println("not fixed");
  else
    System.out.println("fixed");
}
And this:
public static void main(String[] args) {
  String valueToFix = "Howdy!\u0000";
  String valueFixed = valueToFix.replaceAll("\\x00", "");
  if (valueToFix.contentEquals(valueFixed))
    System.out.println("not fixed");
  else
    System.out.println("fixed");
}
I still don't understand why the second one works, but it does. So: neat!

